<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>


<section xml:id="sec-third" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

  <title>What is a Differential Equation?</title>

  <p>
    <em>Derivatives are used to model changing situations!</em>
  </p>

  <p>
    <em>And things are changing all around us!</em>
  </p>
<example xml:id="ex1">

  <statement>
    <p class="example-title">
      Example 1. Come up with an equation that models the following situation:
    </p>

    <p>
      The rate of change of a population <m>P(t)</m> (where <m>t</m> is time in years)
      is proportional to current population. The constant of proportionality is 3.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>hey</p>
  </solution>

</example>
  <p>
    The equation above representing how the population is changing is an
    example of a <term>differential equation</term>. We say the
    <term>order</term> is 1 because the highest-order derivative appearing
    is a first derivative.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-differential-equation">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>differential equation</term> is an equation involving a
        function, its derivatives, and independent variable.
      </p>

      <p>
        The <term>order</term> of a differential equation is the highest
        derivative appearing.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <remark xml:id="remark-general-solution">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A simple model of a population <m>P(t)</m> is that the rate of
        change is proportional to the population. So,
        <m>P(t)</m> satisfies
      </p>

      <me>
        \frac{dP}{dt} = kP
      </me>

      <p>
        The <term>general solution</term> to this differential equation is
      </p>

      <me>
        P(t) = Ce^{kt}
      </me>

      <p>
        where varying over any real number for <m>C</m> gives all possible
        solutions.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </remark>

  <p>
    With the proper <term>initial conditions</term> we obtain a
    <term>specific solution</term> to a differential equation.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="example-initial-value-problem">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose a population <m>P</m> satisfies
        <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 2P</m>, and the initial population at
        <m>t = 0</m> is <m>P(0) = 200</m>. Find the solution
        <m>P(t)</m> to this <em>initial value problem</em>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        Placeholder solution text goes here.
      </p>

      <p>
        Start with the general solution and use the initial condition to
        determine the constant.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

</section>